observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the LCE require the 

(a) Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Engineering Office and the BAC to 

(i) immediately submit the bidding documents to the Audit Team to preclude the noted transactions from being suspended in audit; 

(ii) hold the concerned contractors liable for liquidating damages on negative slippage in accordance with Annex D of the CY 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184, if warranted; and 

(b) Municipal Engineer to 

(i) submit a written explanation/ justification on the noted observations/deviations on implemented projects; 

(ii) ensure that the schedule of activities for all construction are in accordance with the detailed engineering designs and programs; 

(iii) ensure that the necessary documents for civil works in case of temporary work suspensions are prepared and duly approved; (iv) check the progress of the construction at all reasonable times during the project implementation stage to avoid negative slippage; and 

(v) comply with the standard rates prescribed by DPWH DO No. 197 series of 2016 in the preparation of the ABC.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agree to a) require the Municipal Budget Officer, together with the focal person and focal departments/offices, to appropriately allot 5% for GAD-related activities in accordance with PCW-NEDA and DBM Joint Memorandum No. 2012-01; 

b) direct the focal offices to submit to the Audit Team the GAD Accomplishment Report within five working days from end of January of the ensuing year; and 

c) require the focal persons to make a clear assessment of the GAD PPAs for monitoring and evaluation of the GAD implementations.

We recommended that Management:

adhere strictly to all applicable laws, rules and regulations affecting cash advances;

see to it that only appointed and designated disbursing officers perform disbursing functions;

prohibit the granting of cash advances to elective officials other than those authorized by law and regulations; and

comply strictly with the guidelines and principles of imprest fund system wherein regular, recurring, and non-petty expenses should all be paid in check in the name of the supplier for internal control purposes so that the applicable taxes may be deducted from the payment of purchases.

We recommended that Management:

prioritize the conduct of a complete inventory and the reconciliation of the results thereof with the accounting records;



require the Municipal Accountant to provide depreciation on all depreciable assets of the Municipality; 

require the Accounting Office and Treasury Office/GSO to maintain the appropriate subsidiary property records such as PPELC and PLC, respectively;



require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to reconcile their records to be able to account for all lots owned by the Municipality to pave the way for the recording of the necessary adjustments in the books; and



prioritize the reproduction of the titles on all lots owned by the Municipality.

We recommended that Management:

observe the conditions and procedures provided by existing laws, rules and regulations in hiring consultants to minimize expenditures; 

ensure that the duration of the contracts of consultants hired by virtue Section 53.7 of IRR of R.A. 9184 be limited to six months renewable at the option of the Head of the Procuring Entity, so that unnecessary consulting services may be terminated at the earliest opportunity; 

instruct consultants to submit quantified/comprehensive accomplishment reports which must be signed by them and noted by the concerned department head; and

require the refund of the irregular expenditures incurred and hold the concerned officials  liable thereof.

We recommended that Management:

require the submission of lacking documents to support the transactions made;

prohibit the practice of procuring goods and services thru reimbursement unless the item/service is petty in nature;  

comply strictly with the guidelines and principles of an imprest fund wherein regular recurring and non-petty expenses should all be paid in check in the name of the supplier for internal control purposes and so that the applicable taxes may be deducted from the purchases; and


designate an inspection officer to conduct inspection of all deliveries.

In view of the above observations, we recommend that Management:

formulate a concrete waste management plan in conformity with R.A. 9003; 

establish Materials Recovery Facility (MRF) in every barangay or cluster of barangays in accordance with Section 32, Article 4 of R.A. No. 9003;




strictly implement at the household level the no segregation no collection policy in accordance with the Act;





reconstitute the Solid Waste Management Board pursuant to Section 12 of R.A. No. 9003 and deputize Solid Waste Management Officers to enforce the requirements of laws, rules and regulations concerning environment; and

require the training and capacity building of the deputized Solid Waste Management Officers at the National Ecology Center to gain familiarization with environmental laws and strategies.

